Citation.sTitle: Heat capacities, third-law entropies and thermodynamic functions of the negative thermal expansion material Zn2GeO4 from T=(0 to 400) K
Citation.sAbstract: The molar heat capacity of Zn2GeO4, a material which exhibits negative thermal expansion below ambient temperatures, has been measured in the temperature range 0.5(T/K)400. At T=298.15 K, the standard molar heat capacity is (131.86 +/- 0.26) J ? K-1 ? mol-1. Thermodynamic functions have been generated from smoothed fits of the experimental results. The standard molar entropy at T=298.15 K is (145.12 +/- 0.29) J ? K-1 ? mol-1. The existence of low-energy modes is supported by the excess heat capacity in Zn2GeO4 compared to the sums of the constituent binary oxides.
